A few things jump out at me. First, you’re returning an `Err` inside the handler, which will cause a panic because of the missing `?` operator or `.unwrap()` call. Second, JWT creation should be extracted into a separate function for clarity and reusability.

```rust
async fn login(
    axum::Json(payload): axum::Json<LoginRequest>,
    State(state): State<AppState>,
) -> Result<impl IntoResponse, ApiError> {
    let user = match state.users.get(&payload.username).await {
        Some(u) if u.password == payload.password => u,
        _ => return Err(ApiError::Unauthorized("Invalid credentials")),
    };

    let token = create_jwt_token(user.id);

    Ok(Json(LoginResponse { token }).into_response())
}
```
Also, make sure your `ApiError` enum implements `IntoResponse`, or use the error middleware provided by `axum` to handle errors gracefully.
